HEADWORD: Subvene
<hw>Sub*vene"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Subvened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Subvening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>sub-</ets>
+ L. <ets>venire</ets> to come. See <er>Subvention</er>.]</ety> <def>To
come under, as a support or stay; to happen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A future state must needs <qex>subvene</qex> to prevent the whole
edifice from falling into ruin.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Warburton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subventaneous</ent>⟦br⟧
